st foreign-born ethnic groups in the city around 1900—the authors analyze the origins of the immigrants and chart how their lives changed, and explore how immigrant women shaped the urbanization process, creating vibrant public spheres for ethnic expression.In concise social histories of four European rural cultures, the authors emphasize the crucial effects of gender. They explore the contrast between each regional culture of origin and the urban experience of ethnic communities in Chicago. The concept of assimilation, they suggest, involves two different dynamics. In the initial phase, adaptation, the new environment demands major changes of incoming immigrants to meet basic needs. The second dynamic, acculturation, involves changes for immigrants and also for the new culture with which they interact.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aWomen immigrantszIllinoiszChicago. 0aWomenzEurope, NorthernxSocial conditions. 4aU.S. History. 4aWomens Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh1 aBlaschke, Monika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarzig, Christiane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarzig, Christiane, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKnothe, Maria Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMageean, Deirdre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatovic, Margareta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172554840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501725548423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501725548/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell Un